TITLE: Sleepy Corner of U.K.’s Pension Industry Forced the Bank of England’s Hand
SUMMARY: Complex financial instruments that pension funds use to minimize the impact of interest rate changes led to the bond market rout.

TITLE: U.K. Borrowers React to Soaring Interest Rates in Mortgage Market
SUMMARY: The financial turmoil in Britain has led to soaring interest rates, prompting many lenders to withdraw products and stoking worry among homeowners about rising costs.

TITLE: August PCE Inflation Data Shows Prices Are Stubbornly High
SUMMARY: Inflation stayed far above the Federal Reserve’s goal in August, as prices climbed more quickly than economists expected.

TITLE: Stock Market Ends an Ugly Quarter With Another Volatile Day
SUMMARY: The S&P 500 has fallen for three consecutive quarters, the kinds of losses investors have not faced since 2009.

TITLE: Bonds May Be Having Their Worst Year Yet
SUMMARY: This has been the most devastating time for bonds since at least 1926, and maybe in centuries. But, our columnist writes, much of the damage is already behind us.

TITLE: Eurozone Inflation Sets Another Record, Hitting 10 Percent in September
SUMMARY: Jumps in energy and food prices again pushed inflation in the 19 countries that use the euro to the highest annual rate recorded since the currency was created.

TITLE: United Airlines to End Service at J.F.K. Airport
SUMMARY: The airline said it was too small to compete at the airport and would cease flights there at the end of October.

TITLE: Did You Sell an Old Desk Online? You May Receive a Tax Form.
SUMMARY: A law requires online marketplaces to send out a Form 1099-K for sales of $600 or more. Most casual sellers will not owe taxes on the sales, but that’s not always clear.

TITLE: Withholding College Transcripts for Loan Payment Is ‘Abusive,’ Agency Says
SUMMARY: Transcript withholding can make it difficult for students to apply for jobs even if they’ve graduated, since they can’t prove to prospective employers that they have a degree.

TITLE: Price of New A.L.S. Treatment Will Be $158,000 Per Year, Maker Says
SUMMARY: The list price of the therapy, Relyvrio, is much higher than an economic research group recommends, but the company says most patients will pay very little themselves.

TITLE: Half of Adults Have Heard Little or Nothing About New Covid Boosters, Survey Finds
SUMMARY: The latest shots, which target Omicron and its subvariants, could offer protection against a winter surge in cases. But many people are unsure if they’re eligible.

TITLE: Star Maestro With Russian Ties to Depart German Orchestra
SUMMARY: Teodor Currentzis, who has faced scrutiny for his association with a Russian bank, will step down as chief conductor of the SWR Symphony Orchestra in 2025.

TITLE: House Postpones Stock-Trading Vote
SUMMARY: The majority leader’s announcement that the House would not vote this week on a bill to curb trading by members of Congress punted the issue until after the midterm elections and reflected a rough road ahead.

TITLE: Some People Get to Stay Home. Get Over It.
SUMMARY: It may seem unfair that your colleagues have been granted an exception, but resenting them won’t get you a remote-only job.

TITLE: Nick Holonyak Jr., Pioneer of LED Lighting, Is Dead at 93
SUMMARY: He invented a visible red-light diode. His 41 patents also included lasers that enabled DVD and CD players.

TITLE: Can Smartphones Help Predict Suicide?
SUMMARY: A unique research project is tracking hundreds of people at risk for suicide, using data from smartphones and wearable biosensors to identify periods of high danger — and intervene.

TITLE: Consumers kept spending in August amid rising earnings.
SUMMARY: Americans earned more and spent more in August, the latest sign that the economic recovery remains on track despite rising interest rates.

TITLE: The Markets Face a Rare Double Decline
SUMMARY: The losses in tech stocks and bonds is wrecking investor portfolios, and analysts warn of more sell-offs.

TITLE: China Gets Its First mRNA Covid Vaccine Approval — in Indonesia
SUMMARY: Indonesia has cleared an mRNA Covid-19 vaccine developed by a Chinese company. But those types of shots, considered among the most effective, aren’t yet available in China.

TITLE: Health Insurance Guide: Navigating Coverage in Your 20s
SUMMARY: Whether you’re turning 26 and about to age out of a parent’s plan or just landing a job with benefits, finding coverage is a tricky task.

TITLE: NASA May Let Billionaire Astronaut and SpaceX Lift Hubble Telescope
SUMMARY: Jared Isaacman, who traveled to orbit on the Inspiration4 mission, is pursuing a private space program in collaboration with Elon Musk’s rocket company.

TITLE: David Gottesman, Wall St. Power and Warren Buffett Partner, Dies at 96
SUMMARY: He founded the investment house First Manhattan and, after befriending him in the 1960s, pursued enormously lucrative deals with Mr. Buffett.

TITLE: FDA Approves ALS Treatment Despite Questions About Effectiveness
SUMMARY: The drug is safe, and one trial found it may extend survival and slow paralysis in functions like muscle control and speaking. A larger trial will be completed in 2024.

TITLE: China’s ‘Absurd’ Covid Propaganda Stirs Rebellion
SUMMARY: The use of propaganda in the country has been on overdrive in the pandemic, with some Chinese citizens arguing the language has bordered on “nonsense.”

TITLE: US Penalizes Chinese Companies for Aiding Iran’s Oil Exports
SUMMARY: The move suggests a more aggressive approach by the Biden administration after talks to revive a 2015 nuclear deal faltered.

TITLE: Republican-led States Sue to Block Biden’s Student Loan Debt Relief
SUMMARY: The lawsuit accuses President Biden of overstepping his authority in directing the government to cancel as much as $20,000 in student loan debt for millions of people.

TITLE: Fed Announces Plan to Assess Climate Risks to Banks
SUMMARY: The Federal Reserve will put big banks through climate scenario tests next year, but the exercises will not force banks to raise capital.

TITLE: Stocks Drop as Focus Shifts Back to a Potential Recession
SUMMARY: Investors are worried about a global slowdown as central bankers take a hard line against inflation, looking to cool the economy by raising interest rates.

TITLE: Even as Oil Prices Ease, U.S. Keeps Tapping Strategic Reserve
SUMMARY: The administration’s move has brought down gasoline prices. Some experts say continued withdrawals could test the nation’s energy security.

TITLE: Porsche Shares Jump in Blockbuster Market Debut
SUMMARY: Volkswagen spun off the German carmaker on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange, where its stock began trading higher despite a broader decline in European markets.

TITLE: U.S. Economy Weaker Than Thought in Year’s First Half, by One Measure
SUMMARY: Gross domestic income, adjusted for inflation, grew more modestly than first estimated. Unlike gross domestic product, though, it remained positive.

TITLE: German Inflation Soars to Double Digits for First Time in Decades
SUMMARY: Consumer prices rose 10.9 percent over the year through September, much higher than expected, driven by high energy and food prices.

TITLE: Hurricane Ian’s Devastation Shows the Challenge of Pricing Climate Risk
SUMMARY: As severe weather events become more frequent, pricing the risk associated with them will only get trickier.

TITLE: Book Review: “When McKinsey Comes to Town,” by Walt Bogdanich and Michael Forsythe
SUMMARY: “When McKinsey Comes to Town,” by the Times reporters Walt Bogdanich and Michael Forsythe, argues that the legendary firm has accrued an inordinate amount of influence chasing profits at the expense of moral principle.

TITLE: Porsche Takes off in Trading Debut
SUMMARY: Shares in the sportscar maker gained on Thursday, outperforming the wider market.

TITLE: Hand-Painted Billboards in the Age of Digital Ads
SUMMARY: As digital fatigue from the pandemic grows, hand-painted billboards are making a comeback.

TITLE: Physician Burnout Has Reached Distressing Levels, New Research Finds
SUMMARY: Nearly two-thirds of doctors are experiencing at least one symptom of burnout, a huge increase from before the pandemic. But the situation is not irreparable, researchers say.

TITLE: How McKinsey Got Into the Business of Addiction
SUMMARY: The consulting firm’s work with opioid makers is well known, but for decades McKinsey worked with Big Tobacco and has also advised Juul, the e-cigarette company.

TITLE: New Infectious Threats Are Coming. The US Probably Won’t Contain Them.
SUMMARY: The coronavirus revealed flaws in the nation’s pandemic plans. The spread of monkeypox shows that the problems remain deeply entrenched.

TITLE: Britain’s Gamble on Tax Cuts has Economists Warning of Past Mistakes
SUMMARY: Liz Truss, Britain’s new prime minister, defended her plan in the face of stiff criticism from the International Monetary Fund and others.

TITLE: Newsom Signs California Bill to Ease Farm Union Voting
SUMMARY: The governor’s decision, after a veto last year, will allow mail voting in unionization elections. President Biden had pushed for approval.

TITLE: Bill Plante, CBS News’s Man at the White House, Dies at 84
SUMMARY: He covered four presidencies in a 52-year career and never worried about “offending those in power in pursuit of answers,” one former White House press secretary said.

TITLE: Sabotaged Pipelines and a Mystery: Who Did It?
SUMMARY: An attack on gas lines under the Baltic Sea exposes the vulnerability of an already jittery Europe. Some officials suggested Moscow was to blame, but with little evidence, others urge caution.

TITLE: What We Know About the Mysterious Nord Stream Pipeline Leaks
SUMMARY: The leaks, which may amount to as much as a third of Denmark’s annual carbon emissions, expose the vulnerability of critical infrastructure as the war in Ukraine continues.

TITLE: Banks Accuse Consumer Regulator of Abuse of Power
SUMMARY: Several banking trade groups have sued the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, claiming it has exceeded its authority with anti-discrimination enforcement.

TITLE: U.S. and Russia Duel Over Leadership of U.N. Tech Group
SUMMARY: Member countries vote on Thursday for an American or a Russian to lead the International Telecommunication Union, which sets standards for new technologies.

TITLE: Why the British Pound Continues to Sink
SUMMARY: The Bank of England had to step in Wednesday after markets deemed a new government economic plan unwise, but the pound has been on a longer slide.

TITLE: Protests in Prague Signal a Troubled Winter Ahead in Europe
SUMMARY: Tens of thousands gathered in the Czech capital for the second such protest in a month, spurred by an energy crisis and rising prices that are affecting countries across Europe.

TITLE: Wall Street rebounds from a week of turmoil.
SUMMARY: The S&P 500 rose at the beginning of trading after six consecutive days of trading, the longest streak since the beginning of the pandemic.

TITLE: MacKenzie Scott, Billionaire Philanthropist, Files for Divorce
SUMMARY: Less than two years after announcing the marriage and their intent to give money away together, Ms. Scott has parted ways with her second husband, a teacher.

TITLE: Lululemon Hopes to Expand Home Fitness Business With Membership Program
SUMMARY: The athleisure brand bought the interactive fitness company Mirror for $500 million in 2020, when at-home workouts were booming because of Covid lockdowns.

TITLE: ‘Act of Sabotage’ Hits Europe’s Energy and Stocks Markets
SUMMARY: Natural gas prices soared in Europe and stocks fell, as officials  investigate the causes of the Nordstream 1 and 2 gas pipeline explosions.

TITLE: To Calm Markets, Bank of England Will Buy Bonds on ‘Whatever Scale Is Necessary’
SUMMARY: The purchases are designed “to restore orderly market conditions,” the central bank said, after days of turmoil that followed the government’s plan for sweeping tax cuts and higher borrowing.

TITLE: Burberry Names Daniel Lee as Its Chief Creative Officer
SUMMARY: The English designer joins the British luxury label, replacing Riccardo Tisci after months of speculation.

TITLE: Can Hong Kong Recover as a Global Metropolis After Pandemic Barriers?
SUMMARY: Officials are saying the city will bounce back. But even before 2020, Chinese control was changing Hong Kong’s character and driving people away.

TITLE: The Crypto World Is on Edge After a String of Hacks
SUMMARY: More than $2 billion in digital currency has been stolen in hacks this year, shaking faith in the experimental field of decentralized finance, known as DeFi.

TITLE: Can a Telehealth Start-Up Add  Support to Pregnancy Care?
SUMMARY: The goal of Poppy Seed Health is to connect underserved pregnant women to nurses, midwives and doulas who can offer on-demand assistance.

TITLE: Chinese Billionaire Richard Liu Faces Sexual Assault Trial in the US
SUMMARY: Richard Liu, also known as Liu Qiangdong, will be one of the few high-profile Chinese figures to face a courtroom jury over sexual assault allegations.

TITLE: The Long Road to Driverless Trucks
SUMMARY: Self-driving eighteen-wheelers are now on highways in states like California and Texas. But there are still human “safety drivers” behind the wheel. What will it take to get them out?
